lp before i rip this thing to shreads!!!</span><hr size=1> I'm getting very frustrated with this one, at first i was just messing around drawing legs and feet but i liked how they cam out so i decided to add the upper body (that was probably what started this problem, no first objective). I thought I had a good idea going but i cant seem to get it to look right, especially the cape. Please help<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://img3.ranchoweb.com/images/anisource/capekid.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uanisource.showPublicProfile?language=EN>anisource</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://img2.ranchoweb.com/images/anisource/smileywarz.gif" BORDER=0> at: 9/3/02 1:57:05 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/umichaeldjuhasz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MichaelDJuhasz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/3/02 2:27:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6325.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.sprintmail.com/~tjuhasz/juhaszland/photo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Help before i rip this thing to shreads!!!</span><hr size=1> First off, if his cape is blowing, his hair should be as well.  <br>
<br>
It looks like his legs and torsoe are turned slightly to the side, however his shoulders would suggest otherwise.<br>
<br>
The thumb starts too far out.  It should line up with his index finger.  Also, it would probably cover more of his ring finger, if not the pinkey as well.<br>
<br>
The cape looks kindda flat.  Try to give it some depth by adding something to the sides.<br>
<br>
It is a really cool drawing though, don't get discouraged. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=jennilee>Jenni Lee</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Pre-Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/3/02 2:35:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6325.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Comment</span><hr size=1> My friend, you shouldn't draw the legs and then the body in that order. You should always start with a skeleton and then build from there. Your character looks like he's leaning to the left, which could have been avoided if you had started with a skeleton...and a center of balance. The center of balance for this guy should run from his clavicle to the inside ankle of his supporting foot, and in the position he's standing in, should be straight up and down. His center of balance is teetering to the left, but both feet are planted on the ground!<br>
<br>
As soon as you've got that done, make sure his pose is correct. He looks stiff and ill-planned. A skeleton can right many wrongs before they happen, I assure you. (And I mean a rouch, stick skeleton, not a full drawn skeleton, just in case you don't know. You know, lines for the &quot;bones&quot; and circles for the &quot;joints). <br>
<br>
I also want to comment on his clothes. Dear, when drawing clothes, don't make him look like a cardboard cut out! (I am berating you only because I work with clothes, so you can ignore me if you want...LOL). His clothes seem a bit tight on him, and his pants look like a grandpa's droopy drawers. It's not a bad attempt, don't get me wrong, but minor things can be done to improve it.<br>
<br>
First, his cape: his cape is a large rectangle cloth, I am supposing. You've drawn it so where it appears like the end of his cape is one solid form. Don't be afraid to make it flow and twist and turn in the wind. Give it a bit of perspective. Also, his shirt seems too tight because there are no signs of &quot;ease&quot; around his shoulders, waist, and elbows. Finally, don't be afraid to draw a crotch on the guy. We all have them, and not drawing one makes his pants seem baggy, or worse, something else we don't want to explain is (hint, hint). <br>
<br>
There's an easy way to tackle this problem. Don an outfit similar to this guy's (don't laugh!). Look at how the wrinkles and lines and flowing cloth is shaped around your body, and do a few practice sketches. Be sure to draw the shades and shadows. Take it one step further and practice drawing draped fabrics of all sorts of types, like denim, silk, taffetta, etc. It'll help you in the end.<br>
www.rustyssnakeskin.com <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/us1d.showPublicProfile?language=EN>S1D</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/3/02 5:23:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6325.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Comment</span><hr size=1> yup that happens to me as well when i do the legs first...usually i start with the head, cause i dont like using the skeleton way.  the body seems to be too long in this case, if you count for yourself.  cause from the hips to the feet is double of the head to the hips, either way the body should be traditional 8 heads or 7 heads.  if you cant do the cape shown in the air of the wind blowing from west, then just let the cape fall down like normal in gravity <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=coraxus>Coraxus</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/4/02 8:58:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6325.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Help before i rip this thing to shreads!!!</span><hr size=1> You may say that you botched up in constructing a character in the proper order, but <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> damn</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, you pulled it off well, the anatomy is very good as in proportion and no mistakes could be shown anywhere because of how you drew the character.<br>
<br>
Now since the character looks good, we can focus on how we could improve other aspects. For instance, we can have his hair and his cape blow in the same direction instead of having them being blown in opposite directions.<br>
<br>
Finally, judging from this drawing, I believe you can come up with some dynamic poses so he doesn't have to stand and let the wind blow around him. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uanisource.showPublicProfile?language=EN>anisource</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://img2.ranchoweb.com/images/anisource/smileywarz.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(9/4/02 1:19:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6325.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://img2.ranchoweb.com/images/anisource/chewy.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Help before i rip this thing to shreads!!!</span><hr size=1> I know i drew it way out of order but like i said, i was messing around with feet and shoes and i liked how those looked so i drew a body on them lol (very bad idea). I didnt even catch the thing about the hair and cape being blown in opposite directions though, that was careless of me. Im going to have to work on it a lot more before i ink this apparently, but thanks for all the feedback.<br>
